{h2 Appendix: Quick Reference}

{h3 Pipeline Operators}

{table
  | Operator | Meaning                          | Example                    |
  |----------|----------------------------------|----------------------------|
  | {code |>}     | Pipe: pass left as arg to right  | {code x |> f |> g}              |
  | {code |?}     | Safe pipe: skip if None/Error    | {code user |? get_address |? .city} |
  | {code |>>}    | Parallel pipe (v1.4+)            | {code data |>> process}         |
  | {code then}   | Function composition             | {code (f then g)(x)}            |
}

{h3 Common Stdlib Modules}

{table
  | Module      | Purpose                         |
  |-------------|---------------------------------|
  | {code math}      | Mathematical functions          |
  | {code science}   | Physics constants, ODE, FFT     |
  | {code linalg}    | Matrix / vector operations      |
  | {code stats}     | Statistics: mean, std, CI       |
  | {code crypto}    | Hashing, AES-GCM, PBKDF2        |
  | {code json}      | JSON parse/stringify/path       |
  | {code network}   | HTTP client, URL utilities      |
  | {code graph}     | Graph theory algorithms         |
  | {code signals}   | Signal processing, FFT, filters |
  | {code reactive}  | Signals, Observables, Store     |
  | {code testing}   | Unit test framework             |
  | {code ltlcfg}    | Typed configuration files       |
  | {code watch}     | File watcher / hot reload       |
}

{h3 Pattern Syntax Reference}

{table
  | Pattern        | Matches                              |
  |----------------|--------------------------------------|
  | {code _}            | Anything (wildcard)                  |
  | {code 42}           | Exact value 42                       |
  | {code "str"}        | Exact string                         |
  | {code x}            | Anything, binds to x                 |
  | {code int}          | Any integer                          |
  | {code 1..10}        | Range 1 to 10 (inclusive)            |
  | {code 1..<10}       | Range 1 to 9 (exclusive upper)       |
  | {code [a, *rest]}   | List: head + tail binding            |
  | {code (a, b)}       | Tuple                                |
  | {code Point{x, y}}  | Struct field destructure             |
  | {code A|B|C}        | OR pattern                           |
  | {code p if guard}   | Guard: pattern with condition        |
  | {code p @ name}     | As: match p, bind whole value        |
  | {code /regex/}      | Regex match                          |
}
{h2 Chapter 12: ADT Patterns (v1.5)}

{p
  LATERALUS v1.5 introduces first-class algebraic data types through
  {code Result<T, E>} and {code Option<T>} with full pattern-match support.
}

{h3 Recipe 12.1 — Result-based error handling}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Return either a value or an error from a function
  without using exceptions, and handle both cases at the call site.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn safe_divide(a: float, b: float) -> Result<float, str> {
    guard b != 0.0 else {
        return Result::Err("cannot divide by zero")
    }
    return Result::Ok(a / b)
}

let r = safe_divide(10.0, 0.0)
let msg = match r {
    Result::Ok(v)  => "Answer: {v}",
    Result::Err(e) => "Failed: {e}",
}
println(msg)
}

{p
  {strong Key}: The {code ::} separator distinguishes the enum name from
  the variant. {code Result::Ok(v)} binds the inner value to {code v}.
}

{h3 Recipe 12.2 — Option for nullable values}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Represent an optional value without using nil checks.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn find_user(id: int) -> Option<str> {
    let db = {1: "Alice", 2: "Bob", 3: "Carol"}
    if contains(db, id) {
        return Option::Some(db[id])
    }
    return Option::None
}

let result = find_user(2)
let name = match result {
    Option::Some(n) => n,
    Option::None    => "Anonymous",
}
println("Hello, {name}!")  // "Hello, Bob!"
}

{h3 Recipe 12.3 — Chain Option values}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Call a sequence of functions where each may return
  {code Option::None}, short-circuiting on the first None.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn get_user_city(id: int) -> Option<str> {
    let user    = find_user(id)?            // propagate None
    let profile = load_profile(user)?       // propagate None
    let city    = profile["city"]?          // propagate None
    return Option::Some(city)
}

let city = match get_user_city(5) {
    Option::Some(c) => c,
    Option::None    => "Unknown city",
}
}

{h3 Recipe 12.4 — Type destructuring in match}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Dispatch on a struct type and destructure its fields
  in one step.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
struct Circle  { radius: float }
struct Rect    { width: float, height: float }
struct Triangle{ base: float, height: float }

fn area(shape) -> float {
    return match shape {
        Circle(r)       => 3.14159 * r * r,
        Rect(w, h)      => w * h,
        Triangle(b, h)  => 0.5 * b * h,
        _               => 0.0,
    }
}
}

{h3 Recipe 12.5 — Nested and OR patterns}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Match multiple variants with a single arm, or nest
  patterns for deep destructuring.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
let description = match status_code {
    200 | 201 | 204 => "success",
    301 | 302       => "redirect",
    400             => "bad request",
    401 | 403       => "auth error",
    404             => "not found",
    500 | 502 | 503 => "server error",
    _               => "other",
}
}

{h3 Recipe 12.6 — List head/tail pattern}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Recursively process a list using head/tail destructuring.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn max_list(lst: list) -> int {
    return match lst {
        []              => throw "empty list",
        [x]             => x,
        [head, ...tail] => {
            let rest_max = max_list(tail)
            head > rest_max ? head : rest_max
        },
    }
}

println(max_list([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6]))  // 9
}

{separator}

{h2 Chapter 13: v1.5 Type System Features}

{h3 Recipe 13.1 — Optional Types with Nil Safety}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Handle values that might be absent without runtime crashes.
  Use `int?` syntax for compiler-enforced nil checking.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn find_user(id: int) -> map? {
    let users = {"1": {name: "Alice"}, "2": {name: "Bob"}}
    let key = to_str(id)
    if key in users { return users[key] }
    return nil
}

fn greet(id: int) -> str {
    let user: map? = find_user(id)
    if user != nil {
        // Type narrowing: user is map here (not map?)
        return "Hello, " + user["name"]
    }
    return "User not found"
}

println(greet(1))   // Hello, Alice
println(greet(99))  // User not found
}

{h3 Recipe 13.2 — Generics with Trait Bounds}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Write a generic function that only accepts types satisfying
  a specific interface constraint.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
interface Comparable {
    fn compare(self, other) -> int
}

fn sort_items<T: Comparable>(items: list) -> list {
    // Bubble sort (for illustration)
    let mut arr = items
    let n = len(arr)
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let mut j = 0
        while j < n - 1 - i {
            if arr[j].compare(arr[j + 1]) > 0 {
                let tmp = arr[j]
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1]
                arr[j + 1] = tmp
            }
            j += 1
        }
        i += 1
    }
    return arr
}
}

{h3 Recipe 13.3 — Const Generics for Fixed-Size Types}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Define a matrix type with compile-time dimensions.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
struct Matrix<N: int, M: int> {
    data: list,
    rows: int,
    cols: int,
}

fn new_matrix<N: int, M: int>(fill: float) -> Matrix<N, M> {
    let mut data = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < N * M {
        data = push(data, fill)
        i += 1
    }
    return Matrix { data: data, rows: N, cols: M }
}

let m = new_matrix<3, 4>(0.0)
println(m.rows)  // 3
println(m.cols)  // 4
}

{h3 Recipe 13.4 — Result/Option Pattern Matching}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Use ADT-style pattern matching to handle success/error and
  some/none cases elegantly.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
fn parse_int(s: str) -> Result {
    try {
        return Result::Ok(int(s))
    } catch e {
        return Result::Err("not a number: " + s)
    }
}

fn process(input: str) -> str {
    return match parse_int(input) {
        Result::Ok(n)  => "Got number: " + to_str(n * 2),
        Result::Err(e) => "Error: " + e,
    }
}

println(process("42"))     // Got number: 84
println(process("hello"))  // Error: not a number: hello
}

{h3 Recipe 13.5 — C Backend Transpilation}

{p
  {strong Problem}: Compile Lateralus code to C99 for maximum performance
  or bare-metal deployment.
}

{code lang="lateralus"
// file: math_kernel.ltl
fn fibonacci(n: int) -> int {
    if n <= 1 { return n }
    let mut a = 0
    let mut b = 1
    let mut i = 2
    while i <= n {
        let tmp = a + b
        a = b
        b = tmp
        i += 1
    }
    return b
}

fn main() {
    let result = fibonacci(40)
    println("fib(40) = " + to_str(result))
}
}

{p
  Compile to C with the CLI:
}

{code lang="bash"
# Hosted mode (links libc)
lateralus c math_kernel.ltl -o math_kernel.c
gcc -O2 math_kernel.c -o math_kernel && ./math_kernel

# Freestanding mode (for OS kernels, embedded)
lateralus c math_kernel.ltl --freestanding -o kernel_math.c
}

```
